Description: The National Monument or popularly abbreviated as Monas or Tugu Monas is a 132 meter (433 ft) memorial monument erected to commemorate the resistance and struggle of the Indonesian people to win independence from the Dutch East Indies colonial government. The construction of this monument began on August 17, 1961 under the order of President Soekarno and opened to the public on July 12, 1975. This monument is crowned with a flame covered with gold leaf which symbolizes the burning spirit of struggle. The National Monument is located right in the middle of Medan Merdeka Square, Central Jakarta.

The old town in Jakarta, which is also called Kota Tua, is centered on Alun-Alun Fatahillah, a bustling square with regular traditional dance performances. The Jakarta History Museum is a Dutch-era building with paintings and antiques, while the Wayang Museum exhibits Javanese wooden puppets. Glodok Village, or Chinatown, is famous for its street food, such as dumplings and fried noodles. Nearby are schooners and fishing vessels in the ancient Sunda Kelapa harbour
Dunia Fantasi or also called Dufan is an entertainment place located in the Ancol Dreamland area, North Jakarta, Indonesia. Dufan was inaugurated and opened on August 29, 1985.

Taman Mini Indonesia Indah is a tourist park with the theme of Indonesian culture in East Jakarta. An area of approximately 150 hectares or 1.5 square kilometers is located at coordinates 6?ø18ƒ?ý6.8ƒ??S,106?ø53ƒ?ý47.2ƒ??E

Atlantis Water Adventure, also known as Atlantis Ancol, will present you with an unforgettable water tourism adventure. This 5 hectare themed tourist attraction with water games gives a sensation of adventure in 8 main pools. Namely the Antila pool, Atlas Plaza, Poseidon, Aquarius, Octopus, Kiddy Pool, and Atlantean. Located in the Ancol Jakarta Baycity area, Atlantis can be the right choice of destination for swimming tours.
Taman Impian Jaya Ancol is a tourist attraction in North Jakarta.\n\n

Ragunan Zoo is a zoo located in the Ragunan area, Pasar Minggu, South Jakarta, Indonesia. This 140 hectare zoo was founded in 1864. Inside there are various collections consisting of 295 species and 4040 specimens. reopened on October 11, 2005. This zoo has many rare animal species including cockatoos, orangutans, gorillas, anoa and elephants

Ocean Ecopark One of the Ancol recreation zones that offers green open spaces and experiences and does not forget the educational side for visitors. A variety of fun activities and rides that can be played in a family recreation area, some of which are: Outbondholic, Energy House, Bee House, Canoeing, Paintball, Outbondholic, Eco-Market, Learning Farm, Eco-Bike, Faunaland. If you plan to travel to Ocean Eco Park Ancol, you don't need to worry about the price of the entrance ticket. Because the Ocean Eco Park entrance ticket price is offered at an affordable price.

Marina Ancol Harbor is located in the Ancol Dreamland area, Jakarta. The port, which is commonly called Marina Ancol Pier, is an area that is not only for crossing purposes, but is also being developed for many things, such as water tourism, water sports and playgrounds. The main function of this port is to serve passengers who wish to cross to the Seribu Islands, and vice versa. Many people who live in Jakarta and its surroundings make the Seribu Islands their main tourist destination. Holidays on Pulau Seribu are indeed able to eliminate the fatigue of working in a metropolitan city, while enjoying the beauty of the beaches which are still well maintained. Marina Ancol is located in North Jakarta or in full has its address at Kota Tua, Ancol, Pademangan, City of Jakarta. It's easy to get to this place because it's not too far from the city center. Apart from that, there are many public transportations that go to this place or you can also use online transportation services.
Tidung Island is one of the sub-districts in the South Thousand Islands sub-district, Thousand Islands Regency, Jakarta, Indonesia.
Bidadari Island is one of the resorts in the Thousand Islands Regency, Jakarta. Before it was named Bidadari Island, this island had two names, namely Pulau Sakit and Pulau Purmerend
Pari Island is an island located in the Thousand Islands in the Special Capital Region of Jakarta, Indonesia.

Pramuka Island is one of the islands in the Thousand Islands cluster. This island is the administrative and governmental center of the Thousand Islands Administrative District. Pramuka Island is included in the Panggang Island Village area.

Pelangi Island is an island located in the Thousand Islands in the Special Capital Region of Jakarta, Indonesia. Pelangi Island is an island located in the Thousand Islands in the Special Capital Region of Jakarta, Indonesia, Pelangi Island / commonly called Pulau Petondan Besar (Rainbow Island) is a resort island that is suitable for a vacation. This island resort has a natural concept, because some of its areas are filled with groves of trees that are soothing to the eyes. The beauty of nature and the sea are worth visiting. Surrounded by a grove of trees and clear blue sea, the atmosphere is cool and comfortable. Ideal conditions for traveling with family. With accommodation directly facing the sea, tourists will feel at home for a long time on Pelangi Island. According to information, Pelangi Island or Petondan Besar Island is an island in the Thousand Islands cluster. Administratively, it is part of the Thousand Islands Administrative District, DKI Jakarta province. Along with Petondan Kecil Island is a holiday resort. It is located adjacent to the same cluster as Kelor Island and Kelapa Island. It takes 90 minutes to reach Pelangi Resort from the Mutiara Beach pier. There is a special speedboat at pier R1 Mutiara Beach that takes passengers there. Located 60 ? 70 km from Mutiara Beach, it is quite far. But your trip will pay off once you arrive at Pelangi Island.

Pasar Seni is a craft and arts center which is a place for talented artists to channel their artistic crafts. Artists can meet with art collectors and entrepreneurs to share information and market their products. Founded in early 1977, with the laying of the first stone by Bang Ali Sadikin, the first Governor of DKI Jakarta, in July 1977 to be precise. And inaugurated by Governor H. Tjokropanolo on December 17, 1977. Since the inauguration of the Art Market, it has received a positive response from art lovers which exists.

The Kota Intan Bridge is the oldest bridge in Indonesia which was built in 1628 by the Vereenigde Oostindische Compagnie or VOC government, or our people are more familiar with the Kumpeni title. The bridge is now located in the Kali Besar area of the Old City area of West Jakarta and is under the management of the DKI Jakarta Provincial Tourism and Culture Office.

The Fatahillah Museum, officially known as the Jakarta History Museum, is a museum located at Jalan Taman Fatahillah No. 1, West Jakarta with an area of more than 1,300 square meters. This building was formerly the city hall of Batavia (Dutch: Stadhuis van Batavia) which was built in 1707-1710 by order of Governor-General Joan van Hoorn. This building resembles the Dam Palace in Amsterdam, consisting of a main building with two wings on the east and west and side buildings used as offices, courtrooms, and underground rooms used as prisons. On March 30, 1974, this building was inaugurated by Mr. Ali Sadikin as the Jakarta History Museum.

Museum Bank Indonesia is a museum in Jakarta, Indonesia which is located on Jl. Pintu Besar Utara No.3, West Jakarta (in front of the Beos Kota station), occupying the area of the former Bank Indonesia Kota building which is a cultural heritage from De Javasche Bank with a neo-classical wing, combined with local influences, and was first built in 1828 .\nIn 1625, a simple church was built in this place for Protestants. In 1628, this church was dismantled because it was used for a large cannon when tens of thousands of Sultan Agung's troops attacked Batavia for the first time. This museum presents information on the role of Bank Indonesia in the history of the nation that began before the arrival of western nations in the archipelago until the formation of Bank Indonesia in 1953 and Bank Indonesia policies, including the background and impact of Bank Indonesia policies on society up to 2005. The presentation is packaged in such a way by utilizing modern technology and multi-media, such as electronic displays, static panels, plasma televisions and dioramas so that creating comfort for visitors in enjoying the Museum of Bank Indonesia. Apart from that, there are also facts and collections of historical objects in the period before the formation of Bank Indonesia, such as during the time of the archipelago kingdoms, including collections of numismatic money which were also displayed in an attractive manner. and began to be opened to the public (soft opening) on December 15, 2006 by the Governor of Bank Indonesia at that time, Burhanuddin Abdullah, and the inauguration of phase II (grand opening) by the President of the Republic of Indonesia Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, on July 21, 2009. \nBank Indonesia Museum opens every day except Monday and national holidays.

KidZania is a private Mexican franchise of family entertainment centers currently operating in 23 locations, which allows children to do adult jobs and get paid. KidZania has been visited by over 31 million visitors worldwide since its opening, making it one of the fastest growing global entertainment brands in the world.

The Prasasti Park Museum is a museum of cultural heritage from the Dutch colonial period which is located at Jalan Tanah Abang No. 1, Central Jakarta. This museum has a collection of ancient gravestone inscriptions and miniature tombs typical of 27 provinces in Indonesia, along with a collection of antique hearses. This 1.2 hectare museum is an open-air museum that displays works of art from the past about the sophistication of sculptors, sculptors, calligraphers and writers who were united.
The Puppet Museum is a museum located at Jalan Pintu Besar Utara Number 27, West Jakarta.

The Istiqlal Mosque (literal meaning: Merdeka Mosque) is the national mosque of the Republic of Indonesia, located in the former Wilhelmina Park, in the Northeast of Medan Merdeka Square, in the center of which stands the National Monument (Monas), in the center of the capital city, Jakarta. This mosque is one of the 10 largest capacity mosques in the world which can accommodate more than 200,000 worshippers. On the east side of this mosque stands the Jakarta Cathedral Church. The Daily Chairperson of the Istiqlal Mosque Management Agency (BPMI) as well as the High Priest of the Istiqlal Mosque are Prof. Dr. Nasaruddin Umar, MA The construction of this mosque was initiated by the then President of the Republic of Indonesia, Ir. Sukarno. The laying of the first stone to mark the commencement of the construction of the Istiqlal Mosque was carried out by Ir. Soekarno on August 24, 1961. The architect of the Istiqlal Mosque was Frederich Silaban, a Christian. This mosque has a modern architectural style with marble walls and floors, decorated with geometric ornaments made of stainless steel. The main building of this mosque consists of five floors and one ground floor. The main building is crowned with a large dome with a diameter of 45 meters which is supported by 12 large pillars. A single tower with a total height of 96.66 meters rises in the south corner of the mosque's corridor. This mosque can accommodate more than 200,000 worshipers. Apart from being used as a Muslim worship activity, this mosque is also used as the office of various Islamic organizations in Indonesia, social activities, and general activities. This mosque is also one of the famous tourist attractions in Jakarta. Most tourists who visit are generally domestic tourists in addition to some foreign tourists who are Muslim. Non-Muslim communities can also visit this mosque after previously receiving information about Islam and the Istiqlal Mosque, although non-Muslims are allowed to visit the area and must be accompanied by a guide. , Hijriyah New Year, Birthday of the Prophet Muhammad as well as Isra and Mi'raj, the President of the Republic of Indonesia always holds religious activities at this mosque which are broadcast live on national television (TVRI) and some private television.

Jakarta Cathedral Church, or officially named the Church of Santa Maria Assumption (German: De Kerk van Onze Lieve Vrouwe ten Hemelopneming; English: The Church of Our Lady of the Assumption) is a church in Jakarta. This church building was inaugurated in 1901 and was built with neo-gothic architecture from Europe, namely the architecture that was very commonly used to build church buildings several centuries ago.

The National Museum of the Republic of Indonesia or the Elephant Museum, is an archeology, history, ethnography and geography museum located in Central Jakarta and precisely at Jalan Merdeka Barat 12. This museum is the first and largest museum in Southeast Asia.

Pasar Tanah Abang or Pasar Sabtu was built by Yustinus Vinck on August 30, 1735. Justin Vinck established Pasar Tanah Abang Pasar with permission from Governor General Abraham Patramini. The permit granted at that time for the Tanah Abang Market was to sell textiles and grocery goods and was only open every Saturday. Therefore, this market is called the Saturday Market. This market was able to compete with Pasar Senen (Welter Vreden), which had already advanced. In 1881, the Tanah Abang Market was rebuilt and what was previously open on Saturdays was added on Wednesdays, so that the Tanah Abang Market was opened 2 times a week. The market building was originally very simple, consisting of bamboo walls and planks and a thatched roof of 229 planks and 139 bamboo plots. Tanah Abang Market continued to undergo repairs until the end of the 19th century and the floors began to be hardened with a mortar foundation. In 1913, the Tanah Abang Market was repaired again. In 1926 the Batavian government dismantled the Tanah Abang Market and replaced it with a permanent building in the form of three long booths made of walls and boards and tiled roofs, with the market office located on top of the market building resembling a bird cage. The parking lot in front of the market is a parking lot for horses and carts. There is a large water trough there, and across the street is a shop that specializes in horse fodder. A few tens of meters from the bran shop there is an alley known as Gang Madat, where compactors are localized. During the Japanese occupation, this market barely functioned, and became a place for homeless people. Tanah Abang Market has grown after the construction of Tanah Abang Station. At that location, places such as the Al Makmur Mosque and the Hok Tek Tjen Sien Temple were built, both of which are the same age as Tanah Abang Market. In 1973, Tanah Abang Market was rejuvenated, replaced with 4 four-story buildings, and had experienced two fires, the first on 30 December 1978, Block A on the third floor and the second hit Block B on 13 August 1979. In 1975 it was recorded that there were stalls 4,351 pieces with 3,016 traders.

The Glodok area, which is known as the center of electronic commerce itself, was once the former haunted Glodok Prison. This location is across from Glodok-Pancoran in the Harco area. Before the riots in May 1998, this area had become an electronic shopping center for tourists from Japan, Taiwan and Hong Kong. In Pinangsia, people can find household and building products. Apart from shopping tours, the Glodok-Pancoran Chinatown is also a historical site for the beginnings of the City of Jakarta. After the ethnic Chinese settled and built businesses, as well as sugarcane plantations, Batavia began to grow rapidly.

Seaworld Indonesia is a miniature sea charm contained in the first tourist complex at Taman Impian Jaya Ancol. On October 2, 1992, the Governor of DKI at that time, Wiyogo Atmodarminto laid the first stone for the development of Seaworld Indonesia. In less than two years, on June 3, 1994 SeaWorld Indonesia started operating. The Seaworld area of 3 hectares with a main building area of 4,500 m2 contains various kinds of aquariums, Antasena tunnel (underwater tunnel), library, museum, doctor fish therapy, glow theater, touch screen educational computers containing information on various species at Seaworld and various complementary facilities for visitors such as places to eat, gift shops, and function rooms.

The Agro-Educative Tourism Area ƒ??Cibugaryƒ? Milk Palace (Cibubur Garden Dairy) is a dairy farming agro area with garden and garden nuances. Cibubur Garden Dairy educational tour (CIBUGARY) is an educational tour that is of interest to school students. Educational introduction to cattle farming provides an unforgettable experience for school students. This educational activity, which is not too much and fun, is very much liked by school students. With this educational tour can add knowledge and experience directly for school students. The Cibugary Milk Palace educational tour package costs between Rp. 35,000 to Rp. 65,000 per person. This price includes several bottles of pasteurized milk and cibugary goodybags.

Pecenongan is a culinary paradise in Central Jakarta which has been known since the days when Jakarta was still called the city of Batavia. Previously, in this area there were street vendors selling culinary delights on the side of the road, but year after year the Pecenongan area is getting busier with restaurants that are starting to be built. This Pecenongan area is suitable for those of you who want to have a culinary tour at night, various types of culinary delights that will certainly make you confused about which one to try first. It's no wonder that people who have tried going to culinary here will definitely come back again.

Menteng Park is a park located in the Menteng area, Central Jakarta. This park was formerly occupied by the Menteng Stadium. This park stands on an area of 2.9 hectares, and has a collection of 30 different plant species. Menteng Park also has various supporting facilities such as a playground for children as well as futsal and basketball courts. Uniquely, in this park there are also 44 infiltration wells to help absorb rainwater into the ground.

Do not assume that in Jakarta there are no natural attractions. Immediately go to North Jakarta, to be precise at Kamal Muara Penjaringan or Pantai Indah Kapuk. In this area there is a natural tourism area, namely the Jakarta Mangrove Tourism Park which is now and in recent years being a hit. In this area there are three areas, one in the form of the Muara Angke Wildlife Sanctuary which is closed to the public, the Mangrove Forest which belongs to the DKI Provincial Government but is not so attractive for tourism. Furthermore, the Angke Mangrove Nature Park is indeed a tourism area based on mangrove conservation.

Setu Babakan or Lake Babakan is located in Srengseng Sawah, Jagakarsa sub-district, South Jakarta Municipality, Indonesia near Depok which serves as the center of the Betawi Cultural Village, an area designated for the preservation of Jakarta's cultural heritage, namely the original Betawi culture. 
This Betawi cultural village was founded in dated August 18, 2000 through the Decree of the Governor of DKI Number 92 of 2000 issued by the Governor of DKI Jakarta at that time namely Sutiyoso
Situ Babakan is an artificial lake with an area of 30 hectares (79 acres) with a depth of 1-5 meters where the water comes from the Ciliwung River and is currently used as an alternative tourist spot, for residents and visitors. -nam, and Jengkol. Many Betawi specialties can be found here, including Egg Kerak, Fried Toge, Arum Manis, Duck Rujak, Soto Betawi, Cut Ice, Duren Ice, Pletok Bir, Uduk Rice, Ulam Rice, Lontong Sayur, etc. .
The cultural tourism presented includes typical Betawi houses which are divided into 3 types, the first Betawi house is a warehouse or stable, the second is a Betawi Kebaya or Bapang house, and the third is a Joglo house, almost similar to a typical Yogyakarta house. Lenong, Mask Dance, Tanjidor, Marawis, Gambang Kromong, Lenggang Nyai Dance, and Narojeng Dance. 
Traditional ceremonies in the Betawi Setu Babakan village are Circumcision Bride, Moving House, Khatam Qur'an, and Nujuh Bulan. Setu Babakan is Betawi, with a program from the DKI regional government to improve existing facilities and infrastructure to accommodate the need for green open spaces, as well as areas for water absorption, Setu Babakan is improving itself with full support from the DKI regional government. The function of Setu is not only for preserving Betawi culture which is increasingly eroded by the times, but is also used as an alternative place for recreation which is located in the south of Jakarta. Apart from its main function as a catchment reservoir for South Jakarta,

Suropati Park (originally named Burgemeester Bisschopplein) is the name of a park in Jakarta. Initially the name of this park was taken from the name of the first mayor of Batavia, GJ Bisshop (1916-1920). This park is the center of the Menteng area, located right between the confluence of three main roads, namely Menteng Boulevard (Jalan Teuku Umar), Orange Boulevard (Jalan Diponegoro), and Nassau Boulevard (Jalan Imam Bonjol). The field, which is now known as Taman Suropati, since 1920 has replaced a large round field in the Moojen Plan. Suropati Park, which is touted as the zero point of the Republic of Indonesia, is a shady park and since a few years ago has been decorated with statues by sculptors from the founding countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.

Puring Park is not a literal garden. Since its existence in 1960, Taman Puring is a market. Over the years, this market had become a black market alias market for illegal goods. Between the 1980s and 1990s, this market was increasingly shunned by the public because it became a center for goods resulting from criminal acts. Since it caught fire in 2002, Taman Puring Market has slowly improved itself until now it has become a favorite weekend shopping destination for Jakartans. There are hundreds of men's shoe stalls ranging from leather shoes, mountain shoes, futsal shoes, to slang shoes typical of young people. Various brands ranging from Adidas, Caterpillar, Nike, Karrimor, Vans, to Converse are available in various models and colors.

Grand Indonesia is a mall in Jakarta. This mall was opened in 2007 by President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono. In 2007, Hotel Indonesia underwent a restoration. Furthermore, after reopening, the hotel was managed by the Kempinski group and the name was changed to Hotel Indonesia-Kempinski.

One of Jakarta's ice skating rinks is Taman Anggrek Ice Skating. The ice skating area at Taman Anggrek is made up of 1,248 square meters. The grandest ice skating in Indonesia is at Taman Anggrek. Not only the grandest in Indonesia but also the grandest in Asia. So it's not surprising that so many visitors come.

Cibubur Scout Tourism Campground and Graha (Buperta Cibubur) is a camping area located in Cibubur, Ciracas, East Jakarta. This area has an area of 210 hectares and has been the location for the National Jamboree many times since 1973. Buperta Cibubur was built in an area that was previously a rubber forest. The management also works with the Army and Air Force in the management of the Cibubur Buperta. The Cibubur Buperta can be accessed from the Kampung Rambutan Terminal by public transportation to Kranggan or Mekarsari Jonggol,

Place_Name: State Palace of the Republic of Indonesia
Description: The State Palace is the center of state government activities. Many state activities were held at the State Palace. Such as the inauguration of important state officials, as well as the opening of national and international congresses. The function of the State Palace is more focused on official presidential activities, namely as the office of the President of the Republic of Indonesia. Reported by the website of the Secretary of State (Sesneg), the State Palace was originally the private residence of a Dutch citizen, JA Van Braam.

Place_Name: Macan Museum (Modern and Contemporary Art in Nusantara)
Description: The Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art in the Archipelago or Museum MACAN is an art museum in Kebon Jeruk in Jakarta, Indonesia. This museum is the first in Indonesia to have a collection of modern and contemporary Indonesian and international art.

The National Gallery of Indonesia (English: National Gallery of Indonesia) is a state cultural institution or as a museum of modern and contemporary art. Here there is a building that functions, among other things, as a venue for exhibitions and exhibitions of Indonesian and foreign art. This building is a government-owned institution under the Minister of Education and Culture. The functions of the National Gallery of Indonesia are to carry out studies, collection, registration, maintenance, security, exhibitions, partnerships, educational services and publication of works of art. Then its main function is to protect, develop, and utilize artistic assets (fine arts) as educational and cultural facilities. The National Gallery is located at Jalan Medan Merdeka Timur No. 14 Central Jakarta.

The Maritime Museum is a museum that holds collections related to maritime affairs and Indonesian services from Sabang to Merauke which are located across from Sunda Kelapa Harbour. The museum is one of eight museums under the supervision of the Museum Culture Office of the Special Capital Region of Jakarta.

Place_Name: Museum of Fine Arts and Ceramics
Description: The Museum of Fine Arts and Ceramics (Indonesia: Museum of Fine Arts and Ceramics) is a museum in Jakarta, Indonesia. This museum is specifically dedicated to displaying Indonesian traditional art and ceramics. This museum is located on the east side of Fatahillah Square, near the Jakarta History Museum and the Wayang Museum.

Escape Hunt is a recreation area located in South Jakarta. In this place, you will act as a detective who is in a locked room and only given 1 hour to solve the puzzle. No need to worry or be afraid of being alone, because here you can invite up to 4 of your friends in the same room and solve cases together. Very interesting, isn't it? The first time you arrive at this place, you will be guided to fill in the data in the form provided and given a briefing by the game guide regarding the theme/case storyline that you have determined.

The Selamat Datang Monument is a monument located in the middle of the Hotel Indonesia roundabout, Jakarta, Indonesia. This monument is a statue of a pair of humans holding flowers and waving their hands. The statue faces north which means they welcome people coming from the direction of the National Monument.

If you have visited Seaworld Ancol, you may already be familiar with the thrill of watching marine life. If not satisfied, visitors can try visiting unique marine animal tours at the Jakarta Aquarium. The Jakarta Aquarium occupies an area of ñ7000 m2 and offers modern marine tourism attractions that are not only entertaining but also educative. Although not as large as SeaWorld Ancol, this recreational park also offers rides and attractions that are no less interesting.

Semak Daun Island is one of the islands located in the Thousand Islands cluster. Administratively, this island is included in the Thousand Islands district, DKI Jakarta province as a hawksbill turtle breeding area with comfortable beaches for swimming because the beaches are clean and sloping, white sand, and free of sea urchins, there are also good areas for diving and snorkeling beginners and it is not far from Pramuka Island.

Situ Lembang Park is a city park located in the center of Jakarta. Situ means a brackish lake, while Lembang is the name of the road near the park..\nThis park is one of the oldest parks in Jakarta and has a small lake whose water comes from a natural spring. In this park there are fishing arena facilities, running tracks, and children's play areas. Situ Lembang Park is surrounded by houses in the elite area of Menteng

The Jakarta Arts Center Taman Ismail Marzuki, popularly known as Taman Ismail Marzuki (TIM) is an arts and culture center located on Jalan Cikini Raya 73, Central Jakarta. Here is located the Jakarta Art Institute and the Jakarta Planetarium. In addition, TIM also has six modern theatres, exhibition halls, galleries, archives and cinemas. Art and cultural events are regularly held at this arts centre, including drama, dance, wayang, music, poetry readings, painting exhibitions and film shows. Various types of traditional and contemporary art, both original traditions from Indonesia and from abroad, can also be found in this place. The name of this arts center comes from the name of the famous Indonesian songwriter, Ismail Marzuki.

Galeri Indonesia Kaya (abbreviated as GIK) is a public space that combines educational and digital concepts with the aim of introducing and appreciating Indonesian arts and culture, especially to the younger generation, which is located at Grand Indonesia, Jakarta, Indonesia. Galeri Indonesia Kaya was initiated and built to become a digital technology-based cultural edutainment space that can bring closer and channel the creativity of expression of the younger generation within the scope of the archipelago's cultural traditions. This place has an auditorium that can be used for people who need a place to work.

Gedung Joang '45 or Museum Joang 45 is one of the museums in Jakarta. Currently the management is carried out by the DKI Jakarta Provincial Tourism and Culture Office. This museum is located on Jalan Menteng Raya 31, Kebon Sirih Village, Menteng District, Central Jakarta. This museum was inaugurated in 1974 by President Soeharto, after renovations were carried out.

The Jakarta Planetarium and Observatory is one of three sky simulation rides in Indonesia besides Kutai, East Kalimantan and Surabaya, East Java. This oldest planetarium is located at Taman Ismail Marzuki, Jakarta. Jakarta Planetarium is an educational tourism facility that can present astrological or celestial objects simulation shows/demonstrations. Visitors are invited to wander in the universe to understand the conception of the universe through event after event. The Jakarta Planetarium was established in 1964 initiated by President Soekarno and handed over to the Provincial Government of DKI Jakarta in 1969. In this place there is also an exhibition space for celestial bodies which presents various photographs and complete explanations of various forms of galaxies, theories of galaxy formation accompanied by an introduction to the figures figure behind the emergence of the theory.

KAMPUNG China is a residential and trading area in Cibubur, East Jakarta. This area was established thanks to the collaboration between the City Government of East Jakarta and foreign companies to turn the 300 hectare area of the Cibubur tourist area into a tourist city, independent and town center. Quoting the Jakarta Encyclopedia, the village began operating on September 14, 2002. The buildings, the natural setting, and the trinkets sold still smell of Chinese art. All the products that were colonized also came from the bamboo curtain country. The area will become a tourist destination during Chinese New Year celebrations.

Si Pitung's house in Marunda, North Jakarta, Indonesia, is one of the few remaining Betawi stilt houses. This stilt house is a representation of the stilt dwellings of the Betawi people who live in coastal areas. This house is a museum and is included in the cultural heritage. It is not known exactly when the Si Pitung House was founded. It is estimated that the building was built in the 20th century. The stilt house, which is often also called the Marunda High House, is similar to the traditional house of the Bugis tribe. This house used to belong to Haji Saipudin, a wealthy fish dealer merchant from Makassar (other sources say Haji Saipudin was a sero skipper, or ship conglomerate). Haji Saipuddin is believed to be Si Pitung's close friend. It is believed that Pitung only visited the house several times (estimated to be in the 1890s). Si Pitung's last stop was in order to hide from the pursuit of the Dutch army on charges of robbing. The DKI Jakarta government first restored the stilt house which was supported by 40 pillars in 1972. Previously in the same year the DKI Jakarta Provincial Government bought this building from the descendants (heirs) of H. Saipudin. The building is now a museum and included in the cultural heritage based on Governor's Decree No.475 of 1993 and Ministerial Decree No.140/M/1998. The institution that gave the original Pesisir Betawi house the name Si Pitung is the National Museum.

This 19-hectare park is owned by the Provincial Government (Pemprov) of DKI Jakarta which is managed by the Department of Agriculture and Forestry of DKI. Cilangkap Agro Tourism Park is located on Jalan Raya Cilangkap No.45, East Jakarta. This park feels so beautiful with the growth of various types of shady trees. The cool air, which is far from the pollution of motor vehicle fumes, can also be enjoyed in the park, which is used as an alternative tourist destination for residents living around the area. Cilangkap Agro Tourism Park is also equipped with several facilities such as a sports arena, jogging track, children's playground, and for Ayojakarta friends who have a hobby of fishing, around the park area there is a lake which is usually used as an area for fishing.

Kim Tek Le Temple, or better known as Jin De Yuan Temple, has been built since 1650. The temple which is said to be the oldest in Jakarta was founded by a Chinese Lieutenant, Kwee Hoen and was originally called Koan Im Teng. Jin De Yuan is also known as one of the four major temples managed by Kong Koan or the Chinese Council. They are the Goenoeng Sari Temple, the Toa Peh Kong Temple, the Jin De Yuan Temple itself, and the Hian Thian Shang Temple in Tanah Tandjoeng which is now destroyed.

Ancol Beach is a tourist area which is a beach tourism destination in the city of Jakarta. Tourists can enjoy the fresh atmosphere of Lagoon Beach, Festival, Scenic, Beach Pool and Carnival, as well as Dream Lake. Vacationing in nature is believed to have a calming and pleasant effect. The length of the coastline, which is approximately 6.5 km, is a place for various tourist activities. This beach tourism is the second largest regional revenue-producing BUMD for DKI Jakarta province.

Banteng Field, formerly named Waterlooplein (Dutch: plein = field) is a field located in Weltevreden, Batavia; not far from Jakarta Cathedral Church. At that time, Banteng Field was known as Singa Field[1] because in the center was a monument to the victory of the battle at Waterloo, with a lion statue above it. The Battle of Waterloo took place on 18 June 1815 near the town of Waterloo, which is about 15 km to the south of the Belgian capital, Brussels. The battle was Napoleon's last battle against the combined Anglo-Dutch-German forces. This battle is also recorded in history as the closing of one hundred days since Napoleon fled his exile on the island of Elba. Meanwhile, the Singa Monument was erected during the Japanese occupation government (1942-1945). After Indonesia's independence, the name was changed to Banteng Field. It is possible that in ancient times the place that is now the field was inhabited by various kinds of wild animals such as tigers, deer and bison. When JP Coen built the city of Batavia near the mouth of the Ciliwung, the field and its surroundings were still partly swampy wilderness. On the east side of Jalan Banteng Timur there is the Central Jakarta Police Traffic Unit Office.

Ayodya Park, formerly known as Barito Park, is a city park located in South Jakarta. This park is located on an area of 7,500 m2, equipped with an artificial pond covering an area of 1,500 m2 in the middle. markets such as the Gran Mahakam Hotel, Blok M Plaza, Barito Bird Market, Kebayoran Baru Mall, and Taman Puring Market. This park is adjacent to Langsat Park just by crossing the main road.

The Youth Oath Museum is a museum of the history of the struggle for independence of the Republic of Indonesia which is located at Jalan Kramat Raya No. 106, Central Jakarta and managed by the Ministry of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia. The museum is open to the public, every Tuesday to Friday from 08.00 to 16.00 UTC+7, every Saturday and Sunday at 08.00-16.00 WIB, and every Monday and national holidays, the museum is closed to the public. nThis museum has a collection of photographs and objects related to the history of the 1928 Youth Pledge, as well as activities in the Indonesian national youth movement. The Youth Pledge Museum was established based on the Decree of the Governor of DKI Jakarta in 1972 and has become a national cultural heritage object.

The Textile Love Museum occupies an old building on Jalan KS Tubun / Kota Bambu Selatan No. 4 Palmerah District, West Jakarta\n\nThe building itself was originally a private home of a French citizen built in the 19th century. Then it was bought by a Turkish consul named Abdul Azis Almussawi Al Kazimi who settled in Indonesia. Then in 1942 it was sold to Dr. Karel Christian Cruq. During the struggle for Indonesian independence, this building became the headquarters of the People's Security Front (BKR) and in 1947 was occupied by Lie Sion Pin. In 1952 it was bought by the Ministry of Social Affairs and on October 25, 1975 it was handed over to the Regional Government of DKI Jakarta, which later on June 28, 1976, Mrs. Tien Soeharto inaugurated its use as the Textile Museum.

The Proclamation Monument is a monument commemorating the proclamation of independence of the Republic of Indonesia which stands in the Proclamation Park complex on Jalan Proklamasi, Central Jakarta. The park is located in the former residence of Sukarno at Jalan Pegangsaan Timur 56. The house, which has been demolished, was the location for the reading of the proclamation of independence. In the complex there is also a monument to two large statues of Sukarno-Hatta standing side by side, similar to the photo documentation when the text of the proclamation was first published. read out. In the middle of the two statues of the proclaimer is a statue of the proclamation text made of black marble slabs, with the arrangement and form of the writing similar to the original typewritten text.

Taman Legenda Keong Emas is one of the favorite recreational spots in the East Jakarta area. Located in the location of Taman Mini Indonesia Indah or TMII, TMII's Golden Conch Legend Park has also become an icon in the center of the largest tourist facility in Indonesia. Aside from being a recreational facility for the whole family, TMII's Golden Snail Legend Park also has a vision and mission to educate the public while preserving Indonesia's cultural heritage, one of which is through folklore legends.

The National Awakening Museum (English: Museum of National Awakening) is a building that was built as a monument to the birth and development of national awareness and the discovery of the first modern movement organization with the name Boedi Oetomo. Before becoming a museum, this building used to be a medical school founded by the Dutch under the name School tot Opleiding van Inlandsche Artsen, abbreviated as STOVIA or Bumiputra Medical School. During its journey, the building always changes its function. The location of this museum is not far from Pasar Senen, precisely at Jalan Abdurrahman Saleh No.26, before the Gatot Subroto Army Hospital, Central Jakarta.

The Sasmita Loka Ahmad Yani Museum is a national hero museum located at Jalan Lembang No. 58 and Jalan Laruharhari No. 65, Central Jakarta, DKI Jakarta, Indonesia. The museum is open to the public from Tuesday to Sunday, from 08:00 to 14:00 WIB. Every Monday the museum is closed to the public.

The Basoeki Abdullah Museum contains Basoeki Abdullah's paintings and personal collections such as statues, masks, puppets and weapons. The museum, which is located in South Jakarta, is managed by the Ministry of Education and Culture. Apart from being used for exhibitions, the museum is also used to hold seminars, research, workshops and to publish various forms of publication in the form of catalogs, biographies, collections of articles and research results.

The Kite Museum is a museum located on Jl. H. Kamang No. 38, Pondok Labu, South Jakarta. This museum is the first kite museum in Indonesia. The number of kite collections in the museum is 600, but the number continues to increase as new collections come from regional and foreign servants as well as kites made by the museum employees themselves. The Kite Museum is open every day from 09.00-16.00 WIB. On national holidays the Kite Museum is closed.

The Muara Angke Wildlife Sanctuary is a conservation area based on the Decree of the Minister of Forestry of the Republic of Indonesia Number: 097/Kpts-II/1988, 29 February 1998 in the mangrove forest area on the north coast of Jakarta. Administratively, this area includes the Kapuk Muara Village area, Penjaringan District, North Jakarta Municipality.

Glodok Chinatown, in Petak Sembilan Market, West Jakarta, is a place that sells a variety of Chinese specialties. This area, which is mostly inhabited by Chinese people, is famous for its typical Chinese culinary delights, which are sold by many residents. Starting from basket cakes, dodol cakes, to layer cakes, many are sold here. With prices ranging from IDR 30,000 to IDR 100,000, these three types of cakes are the most frequently purchased cakes to complete Chinese New Year celebrations. According to a source from the seller, they admit that the cakes they sell are imported directly from various regions. Because they come from different regions, these cakes have their own characteristics.

Freedom Library is a book library that is open to the public. Having tens of thousands of book collections arranged on shelves and according to the theme, making it easier to find the book you want. With a modern room design and a calm atmosphere, readers will feel at home for long here. It is enough to register as a member first and it is free of charge (free) you can read books in this library.

The National Library is a library specifically established by the State Government for the purpose of storing state information. In contrast to public libraries, it is rare that the general public is allowed to borrow books. Often a national library holds rare and historical collections. Some of the early libraries could be called national libraries, such as the Library of Alexandria which was the Library of Ancient Egypt. National libraries are often very large and spacious, especially when compared to other ordinary libraries in the country. Some countries that are not independent, but still wish to preserve their special culture generally establish a national library with all the institutional attributes of legal deposits. \nMany national libraries cooperate with the International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions (English: International Federation of Library Associations) and Institutions (IFLA)) to define common tasks, establish and promote common standards and implement projects to help fulfill their duties. National libraries in Europe participate in European Libraries. It is a service of the Conference of European National Librarians (CENL)).\nOne of the first plans of a national library designed by the mathematician, John Dee, in 1556 was shown to Mary I of England with visionary plans for the preservation of old books, manuscripts, and records and the establishment of a national library, but these proposals were not approved.

Cibubur Garden Dairy or commonly known as Cibugary is a dairy cattle and goat farm that has the feel of a garden in the Cibubur area, the owner, Mr. Rachmat Baghory, has the initiative to make this place an agro-educational tour, especially for children.

Waterbom Jakarta is a water game vehicle that is quite popular in the Pantai Indah Kapuk (PIK) area, North Jakarta. The price of the Waterboom PIK entrance ticket is not too heavy on the pocket, only IDR 100 thousand per person on weekdays or IDR 200 thousand on weekends. Waterboom PIK is a favorite tourist attraction during holidays because it offers adequate facilities and has a fairly complete range of water games.

The stamp museum was built in the form of a Javanese-Balinese building on an area of 9,590 m2 and was inaugurated by President Soeharto on September 29, 1983. This museum exhibits a collection of postage stamps from Indonesia and abroad. There is also an antique postal bicycle with the Falter brand made in West Germany in 1950 placed in the foyer of the museum. On the front page there is a globe with a dove carrying a letter which symbolizes that the duties of Perum Pos and Giro reach the whole world.

The Museum in the Middle of the Gardens is a museum storing ñ 4,000 collections of Indonesian and foreign art and history located in the Kemang area, South Jakarta. This museum was built in the middle of a 3,500 m2 garden. This museum is privately owned by Sjahrial Djalil, one of Indonesia's modern advertising figures and founder of the advertising agency Ad Force Inc. In 2013, the museum was selected as the Best Private Museum at the Museum Awards with collections from 63 countries and 26 provinces in Indonesia.[2] The thing that makes this museum different from other museums is the arrangement of the 2,414 collections that are exhibited to visitors, which are placed irregularly in various corners of the room, such as the floor, garden terraces, toilets, outside walls of houses, and so on.

Waterpark that presents imaginative rides with the concept of snowy mountains. Don't miss the best water attractions that are very fun. With an area of about 3 hectares, this tourist spot provides the best water rides. It's not wrong if this water park is in demand and crowded with visitors, especially when the holiday season comes. Visitors can enjoy the excitement of various water attractions with artistic views that cover 70% of the area with snow. Visitors can feel fatigue and fatigue reduced just by witnessing this exotic snow atmosphere. Visitors will be greeted with world-class water recreation with an adventurous concept that will leave you amazed. Presenting a variety of fun activities that can be enjoyed by the whole family of all ages. Not only water games, there are also adrenaline-challenging rides, perfect for those who want to relieve stress.

The presence of Cattleya Park is of course very beneficial for the people of the Capital City, in the midst of a situation of heavy traffic jams, backlogs of work, and pollution that pose a threat to big cities. The location of Cattleya Park is very strategic for those of you who are confused about finding the right place on the weekend. The location of Cattleya Park is near a very famous shopping center, namely Taman Anggrek Mall.

Tebet Park was built in 1960, this park was delayed in 1970 and became an illegal settlement until 2006. Previously, it was called Taman Honda. Not without reason, it was named that because the restoration of this park was carried out in collaboration with PT Honda Prospect Motor and the Provincial Government of DKI Jakarta. The 1,800 m2 park was inaugurated by the governor of DKI Jakarta (at that time) Fauzi Bowo on 28 July 2010. It is a green open space that Jakarta residents can use for their activities. Located between Tebet Barat Raya Street and Tebet Timur Raya Street, Tebet District, South Jakarta Municipality. The park area has a tributary that flows from Pasar Minggu to Manggarai. Tebet Park is also equipped with a number of facilities, such as a playground for children and a place to exercise. For the sports arena itself, there are badminton and jogging tracks. The park which is cared for by these officers also provides prayer rooms, bathrooms, gazebos, and reflexology therapy facilities.

Apart from the Mangrove Forest Park and Pantai Indah Kapuk, one of the parks that has been quite famous for a long time can be found around the University of Indonesia Depok, located on the outskirts of Jakarta, called Srengseng City Forest. As the name implies, this tourist area is located in the Srengseng Kembangan area of West Jakarta, which is close to the Kemayoran, Kebon Jeruk and Crocodile Swamp areas. Srengseng Forest is one of the green natural areas that can be found in the Special Capital Region of Jakarta. However, you need to know that it's not Srengseng Sawah, it's already different. The presence of this City Park provides an important role in the Jakarta natural sector which is currently experiencing quite rapid development.

Spathodea Park Tourism Object in Jagakarsa DKI Jakarta Selatan Jakarta is one of the tourist attractions located on Jl. Kebagusan Raya, Jagakarsa District, South Jakarta City, Special Capital Region of Jakarta, Indonesia. Spathodea Park Tourism Object in Jagakarsa DKI Jakarta Selatan Jakarta is a tourist spot that is busy with tourists on weekdays and on holidays. The main attraction of Spathodea Park is that there are many types of plants planted, both trees and flowers that adorn the garden area. There is a small lake in the middle of the park that will make visitors comfortable. Many public facilities are also available at Spathodea Park such as a jogging track, fish pond, outdoor gym, children's playground, toilets, ample parking and comfortable seating. Spathodea Park is only open from 05.00 ? 18.00 WIB so when it starts at night this park will be closed to the public.

Plaza Indonesia was inaugurated in early 1990, consisting of four floors of upscale shops with an area of 38,050 m2. This shopping center is located at the Hotel Indonesia Roundabout, precisely at the intermediary of Jalan MH Thamrin and Jalan Kebon Kacang Raya in the main business area of Jakarta. Plaza Indonesia is also equipped with the Grand Hyatt Jakarta hotel, a 28-floor five-star hotel which was officially opened at the beginning of the year. 1990. This hotel has more than 300 rooms with a modern minimalist design, exclusive restaurants, and very complete facilities.\nPlaza Indonesia's development continued when Entertainment X'nter opened next door to the existing building targeting the youth market. The two buildings are connected by a bridge surrounded by shops. Now, Plaza Indonesia has been equipped with the office building The Plaza Office Tower and The Keraton Grand Hyatt Residences apartments. Plaza Indonesia was developed by PT Global Land Development Tbk (formerly PT Kridaperdana Indahgraha). Tbk).

Thamrin City or Thamrin City Mall is a large shopping center located in Central Jakarta, which is located ñ 150 meters from the Hotel Indonesia roundabout and ñ 300 meters from Tanah Abang Market, which is located on Jl. Thamrin Boulevard (formerly Kebon Kacang Raya) with access from various directions, including from Jl. Thamrin, Jl. Teluk Betung, as well as from Jl. KH. Mas Mansour

The Satria Mandala Museum is a museum of the history of the struggle of the Indonesian National Army which is located on Jalan Gatot Subroto, South Jakarta. The museum, which was inaugurated in 1972 by the former President of Indonesia, Soeharto, was originally the home of one of the wives of the former President of Indonesia, Soekarno, namely his wife, Ratna Sari Dewi Soekarno. In this museum you can find various collections of war equipment in Indonesia, from the past to the modern such as collections of mines, missiles, torpedoes, tanks, cannons and even helicopters and airplanes (one of which is the Cureng plane which was once flown by Air Marshal Agustinus Adisucipto). \nIn addition, this museum also stores various kinds of historical objects related to the TNI, such as various heavy and light weapons, military attributes, banners and symbols within the TNI environment. Apart from that, this museum also exhibits a stretcher that was used to carry the Commander-in-Chief General Soedirman when he was a guerrilla in pain against the Dutch re-occupation in the 1940s. together with the people crushed the DI/TII separatist gangs in West Java, Central Java, Aceh, South Kalimantan and South Sulawesi in the 1960s. Other facilities at the Satriamandala TNI Museum include a Children's Reading Garden, Souvenir Kiosk, Canteen and a Multipurpose Building with a capacity of 600 seats.

Museums now don't only offer objects of historical and educational value. But it has been transformed into an exciting recreational vehicle with different photo objects. Like the Alive Museum in Ancol. Alive Museum displays various fine arts in the form of 3-dimensional paintings. Where visitors can take pictures with real backgrounds even if only from photos. And because it's 3-dimensional, of course the photo will look real with the object.

Unlike Pecenongan, the BSM Culinary Area is open from 09:00 to 18:00. Located on Jalan MH Thamrin, Central Jakarta, the BSM Culinary Area is a favorite cheap eatery for local residents and tourists. This Jakarta culinary area presents stalls and stalls lined up in one special area. Diners can walk the narrow lanes between each stall to choose a dish. The BSM Culinary Area presents heavy dishes and snacks. Visitors can find meatballs, fried rice, various soups, Padang rice, uduk rice, pecel, sete, warm, gado-gado, and so on. There are also various light dishes and pastries, such as potato donuts, fried mushrooms, fruit soup, french fries and various fried foods. Visitors can take the Trans Jakarta bus corridor 1 (Blok M-Kota) to the Bank Indonesia bus stop, then cross the road near the Bank Mandiri building. From there, the BSM Culinary Area is quite easy to find.

Yogyakarta Smart Park (Javanese: Hanacaraka,ˆ? ˆ??ˆ??ˆ??ƒ??ˆ?ˆ??ˆ??ˆ??ˆ? ˆ??ƒ??ˆ??ˆ?¦ˆ? §ˆ??ˆ?'ˆ??ˆ? ˆ??ˆ?, Ngayogyakarta Smart Park) is a tourist vehicle located in the center of Yogyakarta City, precisely on Jalan Panembahan Senopati No. 1-3, Yogyakarta, in the Fort Vredeburg area. This park combines recreational and educational tourist attractions in one location. Taman Pintar has a playground as well as educational facilities which are divided into several zones. Direct access to the former Shopping Center book center also adds added value to Taman Pintar. This recreation area is very good for children in their developmental stages. In recent years, Taman Pintar has become an alternative tourist spot for the people of Yogyakarta and outside the city. This park, especially for early childhood education, is equipped with digital interactive technology and video mapping which Stimulate children's imagination and their interest in technology. Currently there are 35 zones and 3,500 educational game props.

Ngayogyakarta Hadiningrat Palace or Yogyakarta Palace (Javanese: ˆ? ˆ?®ˆ? ˆ?§ˆ??ˆ??ˆ??ƒ??ˆ??ˆ?¦ˆ?§ˆ??ˆ?'ˆ??ˆ? ˆ? ?ˆ? ƒ??ˆ?ýˆ?›ˆ??ˆ??ˆ??ˆ??ˆ?¨ˆ? ˆ??, translit. Ngayogyakarta Hadiningrat Palace) is the official palace of the Ngayogyakarta Hadiningrat Sultanate which is now located in the city of Yogyakarta . This palace was founded by Sri Sultan Hamengkubuwana I in 1755 as the Yogyakarta Palace/Palace which was newly established as a result of the Islamic Mataram split with the Giyanti Agreement. This palace is a fragment of the Surakarta Hadiningrat Palace from the Surakarta Kingdom (Kingdom of Surakarta). So that the Mataram dynasty was continued by 2 kingdoms, namely the Yogyakarta Sultanate and the Surakarta Sultanate. The total area of the whole Yogyakarta palace reaches 184 hectares, which includes the entire area inside the Baluwarti fort, Lor square, Kidul square, Gladak gate and the Yogyakarta Gedhe Mosque complex. While the area of the kedhaton (palace core) reaches 13 hectares. Although the Sultanate of Yogyakarta officially became part of the Republic of Indonesia in 1945, this palace building complex still functions as the residence of the sultan and his royal household who still carry out the imperial tradition to this day. This palace is now also a tourist attraction in the city of Yogyakarta. Part of the palace complex is a museum that houses various collections belonging to the empire, including various gifts from European kings, replicas of palace heirlooms, and gamelan. In terms of its building, this palace is one example of Javanese palace architecture of the best, has a luxurious hall, conference hall and a wide field and pavilion.

Sindu Kusuma Edupark (SKE) is a recreational destination located in Jogjakarta. In the seven hectares of the park area which was completed in 2014, there are various kinds of rides, both play rides and learning rides that can be enjoyed by all family members. SKE's most famous ride is the Ferris wheel, which is both a playground and an icon of SKE itself. If Singapore has a Flyer as high as 165 meters, while Malaysia has an Eye as high as 88 meters, and in Thailand there is an Asiatique as high as 60 meters, Indonesia has Cakra Manggilingan with a height of 48 meters. At the Southeast Asian level, this Ferris wheel must be content with sitting in sixth place as the tallest Ferris wheel, but at the national level, it sits in first place.
